subSubSection.paragraph:
In typically coloured specimens pronotal disc black with two smal yellow spots at base, scutellum black, elytral disc yellow with three broad, black vittae, along suture and along sides, connected on slope but marginal interval and apex of disc yellow (
figs 31–33
). In common form named ab. 

baumanni

dorsum uniformly yellow (
fig. 39
). Between these forms many intermediates were observed (
figs 34–38
): often black on pronotal disc forms only triangular spot with two large basal yellow spots (
figs 34, 36
, 
37
) or is reduced to three basal stripes (
fig. 35
), elytral vittae sometimes narrow and not connected apically (
figs 34–36
), or reduced to short rudiments of lateral vittae or spots at base and posterolateral parts of disc (
fig. 37
), occasionally only pronotum with M-shaped pattern but elytra uniformly yellow (
fig. 38
). In southern parts of distribution range predominate forms with pronotal pattern reduced to three or four spots and elytral lateral vittae divided into 3–5 separate spots (
figs 40–42
), sometimes also separate spot on humeral callus and small additional spot in 1/5 length of second interval (
fig. 40
), sutural vitta from broad with irregular sides to very narrow, limited to sutural margin, or completely obsolete (= ab. 

breviuscula

). Explanate margin always yellow. Head usually black, sometimes brown, or area between clypeal grooves brown and central plate black, thorax black, abdomen black narrowly surrounded by yellow. Coxa usually black, trochanters more or less infuscate, rest of legs yellow. Antennae yellow, sometimes last segment infuscate apically.

Pronotum elliptical (
figs 31, 32, 34–42
), with maximum width in the middle, anterior margin regularly convex, sides broadly rounded, no basal corners. Surface of disc impunctate or with extremely fine sparse pricks, shiny. Explanate margin broad, impunctate, shiny, transparent with well visible honeycomb structure.

Base of elytra much wider than base of pronotum (
figs 31, 32, 34–42
), humeral angles distinctly protruding anterad, subangulate, in some specimens elytral margin behind humeral angle shallowly emarginated, then humeri subacute. Disc regularly convex in profile with top of convexity in postscutellar point (
fig. 33
), without impressions. Punctation fine, arranged in regular rows, from sparse to moderately dense, distance between punctures from as wide as to three times wider than puncture diameter. Marginal row distinct, its punctures distinctly coarser than punctures in central rows. Intervals flat, three to five times wider than rows, marginal interval 1.5–2.0 times wider than submarginal one, no humeral or lateral folds. Explanate margin narrow, strongly declivous, in the widest part 5.5–6.0 times narrower than disc, surface usually impunctate but in some specimens with very shallow sparse punctures, shiny, transparent with well visible honeycomb structure.
